description: From Middle English, from Middle French immun, from Latin immūnis (“exempt from public service”), from in- (“not”) + mūnus (“service”).

adjectives.description: immune (comparative more immune, superlative most immune)

examples: As a diplomat, you are immune from prosecution.

entries.meaning: (medicine, usually with "to") Protected by inoculation, or due to innate resistance to pathogens.
examples: I am immune to chicken pox.
Alas, he was immune to my charms.

entries.meaning: (medicine) Of or pertaining to the immune system.
examples: We examined the patient's immune response.

entries.meaning: (epidemiology) A person who is not susceptible to infection by a particular disease

verbs.description: immune (third-person singular simple present immunes, present participle immuning, simple past and past participle immuned)

examples: In the seventies those who met me did not know / Of the vision / That immuned me from the chillings of mis-prision  […]
